## Image and template management
- Per the Design principles above: every VM and container uses a purpose-built image with all packages baked in. Images are REQUIRED — provision roles verify existence and hard-fail if missing. Configure roles NEVER install packages at runtime.
- ALL images are stored locally in `images/` (gitignored) and uploaded to Proxmox during provisioning. NEVER depend on remote downloads from the Proxmox host.
- `build-images.sh` is the current image build script (OpenWrt via Image Builder). Future services will have their own build steps (Dockerfiles, Packer, debootstrap, etc.).
- VM images: uploaded to `/tmp/`, decompressed if `.gz`, imported via `qm importdisk`, then deleted.
- LXC templates: uploaded to `/var/lib/vz/template/cache/` via `ansible.builtin.copy`. The `proxmox_lxc` role checks `pveam list` and skips upload when the template is already cached.
- NEVER delete LXC templates in molecule cleanup. Templates are large (140-315MB each) and identical between runs. Deleting them forces re-upload of ~820MB across all hosts on every test cycle. Template deletion is ONLY valid in production cleanup behind `[full-restore, clean]` tags.
- NEVER use `pveam download` — the host may lack internet (router VM destroyed) or have unreachable enterprise repos (no subscription).
- Image paths are defined in `group_vars/all.yml` (e.g., `openwrt_image_path`, `openwrt_lxc_template_path`). Roles verify the image exists and fail with a clear message pointing to `./build-images.sh` if missing.
- ALWAYS use `role_path` for source paths in tasks. Bare relative paths break when Molecule runs from non-default scenarios.
- Use `./build-images.sh --only <target>` to rebuild a single image (~2-3 min vs ~15 min for all). Targets: mesh, router, pihole, rsyslog, netdata, wireguard.
- See `vm-lifecycle` skill, Image management section, for the full pattern.

## NTP synchronization
- ALWAYS check clock skew BEFORE running the full NTP sync sequence. Use `chronyc -n tracking | awk '/System time/{print $4}'` to measure skew. Only sync when skew > 30 seconds.
- NEVER run unconditional NTP burst+sleep+makestep sequences. Each sync takes ~7s per host. With 4 hosts and multiple sync points, unconditional syncs waste 60-90s when clocks are accurate.
- Set `cache_valid_time: 86400` (24h) for `ansible.builtin.apt` tasks on test machines, not 3600 (1h). Short intervals trigger unnecessary `apt-get update` calls between test cycles.

## pct_remote performance
- Each `pct_remote` task opens a new paramiko SSH connection to the Proxmox host, then spawns `pct exec`. Overhead: 15-60s per task.
- MINIMIZE configure role task count for LXC containers. Base system config that is identical across containers MUST be baked into the image, not deployed via the configure role.
- Configure roles should ONLY contain host-specific config (IPs, streaming endpoints, passwords, optional features gated on env vars).
- Previous bug: systemd override deployed via configure role (3 tasks × 4 nodes = 12 pct_remote calls) added ~12 minutes. Moving to image-only saved 38% of per-feature test time.

## Hardware detection: hard-fail over graceful degradation
- ALWAYS prefer hard-fail when expected hardware is missing. Graceful degradation masks real problems.
- iGPU: REQUIRED on every host. `proxmox_igpu` hard-fails if absent. Supports both Intel (i915) and AMD (amdgpu).
- WiFi + VT-d/IOMMU: REQUIRED for PCI passthrough. `proxmox_pci_passthrough` hard-fails if IOMMU is not active after reboot or if IOMMU groups are invalid.
- NIC count: OK to handle dynamically — hardware legitimately varies (1 NIC on mesh satellites, 3+ on router nodes). The 2-bridge minimum is gated on `router_nodes` group membership.
- Previous bug: `proxmox_pci_passthrough` "gracefully skipped" WiFi passthrough when IOMMU groups were invalid. The real cause was VT-d disabled in BIOS on mesh1. The silent skip masked a fixable BIOS setting for an entire test cycle.

## Baseline workflow
- The OpenWrt baseline on the primary host is expensive to rebuild (~4 min). Layered scenarios (`mesh1-infra`, `openwrt-security`, etc.) depend on it.
- Use `molecule converge` + `molecule verify` for day-to-day iteration. This leaves the baseline running so leaf nodes (mesh1) remain accessible.
- Use `molecule test` only for clean-state validation (CI, pre-commit). It destroys everything.
- After a full `molecule test`, re-run `molecule converge` to restore the baseline before working on layered scenarios.

## Testing requirements
- ALWAYS run `molecule test` after changing roles, playbooks, or molecule config
- ALWAYS update `molecule/default/verify.yml` with assertions for new/changed behavior
- Verify completeness: every configured feature needs an assertion ("VM is running" is NOT sufficient — also check DHCP, NIC topology, auto-start, services, backup manifest, state files)
- NEVER consider a task complete until `molecule test` passes with exit code 0
- ALWAYS run `pytest tests/ -v` after modifying `build.py` — every public function and error path needs coverage
- Run `ansible-lint && yamllint .` before deploying to hardware
- See `.cursor/skills/ansible-testing/SKILL.md` for full details

## Cleanup philosophy: service-specific, not scorched-earth
- Molecule cleanup MUST destroy VMs/containers using **explicit VMIDs** from `group_vars/all.yml`. NEVER iterate `qm list` / `pct list` to destroy ALL resources. Check existence first with `qm status` / `pct status`, then stop + destroy.
- When adding a new service, add its VMID to the cleanup lists in `molecule/default/cleanup.yml`, `molecule/default/cleanup_lan_host.yml`, `tasks/cleanup_lan_host.yml`, and the per-feature scenario cleanup.
- Molecule cleanup MUST NOT restore the host config from backup archive. Explicit file removal is sufficient. Backup restore is only for production cleanup behind `[full-restore]` tags.
- Previous bug: blanket `qm list` / `pct list` cleanup destroyed non-project resources, forced full rebuild of every VM/container on every test run, and was slower than explicit VMID lookup.

## Systemd sandboxing in LXC containers
- Many Debian packages ship systemd unit files with sandboxing directives (`LogNamespace`, `ProtectSystem`, `ProtectHome`, `ProtectControlGroups`, `BindReadOnlyPaths`, `RuntimeDirectory`) that require mount namespace creation. Inside LXC containers, these fail with exit code 226 (NAMESPACE) unless the container has `nesting=1` feature.
- ALWAYS add `features: nesting=1` to LXC containers that run services with systemd sandboxing. This is NOT optional for Netdata, rsyslog, and most Debian services.
- Even with `nesting=1`, some directives like `LogNamespace` still fail. Bake a systemd drop-in override into the image during `build-images.sh` to disable problematic directives: `LogNamespace=`, `ProtectSystem=false`, `ProtectHome=false`, `ProtectControlGroups=false`, `BindReadOnlyPaths=`. Do NOT deploy this in the configure role — it's base system config, not host-specific topology.
- NEVER try to clear systemd directives with empty strings for boolean-like settings. Use explicit `false` values (e.g., `ProtectSystem=false`, not `ProtectSystem=`).
- Previous bug: Netdata service exited 226/NAMESPACE in an LXC container even as privileged. Root cause: `LogNamespace=netdata` in the Netdata systemd unit. Fix: nesting=1 feature + systemd override baked into image.
- Previous bug: systemd override deployed via configure role (pct_remote) added 3 slow tasks per container. With 4 nodes, this added ~12 minutes to molecule test. Moved to image-only.

## Host metrics via LXC bind mounts
- Bind mounting host `/proc` and `/sys` into LXC containers for monitoring requires BOTH: (1) privileged container (`unprivileged: false`) and (2) `nesting=1` feature.
- Mount entries use full Proxmox mount specs: `/proc,mp=/host/proc,ro=1` — the `ro=1` flag makes them read-only.
- The monitoring agent's config must point to `/host/proc` and `/host/sys` (baked into the image) so it reads host metrics, not container-local metrics.
- Previous bug: unprivileged container with bind mounts — extraction failed (disk full at 1GB) and systemd sandboxing prevented service startup.

## LXC container disk sizing
- ALWAYS verify the compressed template size fits the target rootfs. A vzdump archive reports its compressed and extracted sizes, but the rootfs must have headroom for runtime data.
- Netdata's Debian 12 template is ~314MB compressed, ~1013MB extracted. A 1GB rootfs is too small — extraction fails partway through (tar errors on SSL certs). Use 2GB minimum.
- Previous bug: Netdata template built via vzdump produced a 314MB archive. `pct create` with 1GB rootfs failed mid-extraction because the expanded content exceeded the disk.

## Wake-on-LAN recovery
- `wol.sh` is a utility script for remotely waking Proxmox hosts. It is a LAST RESORT for recovering from power outages — not a substitute for proper UPS or IPMI.
- WAN hosts (home, ai, mesh2) receive magic packets via local L2 broadcast from the controller.
- LAN hosts (mesh1) receive magic packets via proxy: the script SSHes to the primary host and sends the packet from there (Python 3 socket, no extra packages needed).
- WoL requires: (1) NIC with WoL support, (2) WoL enabled in BIOS, (3) `ethtool Wake-on: g` on the management NIC, (4) the machine in standby (S5) with power connected.
- USB ethernet adapters do NOT support WoL. The USB host controller is powered down in S5 and lacks magic packet detection circuitry. Hosts with USB-only networking (e.g., ai) require manual power-on or an alternative like a smart plug.
- NEVER test WoL as part of the regular test suite. WoL is destructive (requires the host to be down). Only test it manually or in a dedicated recovery scenario.

## Entry point convention
- `build.py` is the SINGLE entry point for running Ansible. ALL shell scripts MUST delegate to it.
- NEVER call `ansible-playbook` directly from `run.sh` or `cleanup.sh`.
- `build.py` handles: env file parsing (with quote stripping), required var validation, host probing with state file fallback, and playbook resolution. Bypassing it loses all of these.
- See `.cursor/skills/build-conventions/SKILL.md` for patterns and test requirements.
